How to Call Any Oracle BIP Report via Postman (SOAP runReport)

What You Will Learn
By the end of this guide you will be able to:

✅ Call any Oracle BIP report programmatically using Postman
✅ Pass parameters to filter report output (by name, date range, or multiple values)
✅ Decode the Base64 response to read the actual report data
✅ Understand how this SOAP call fits into a larger OIC integration flow

Background — What is the BIP SOAP API?
Oracle BI Publisher exposes all reports through a single SOAP web service endpoint:
POST /xmlpserver/services/ExternalReportWSSService
You call it by sending a SOAP XML envelope that tells BIP:

Which report to run (the catalog path)
Which parameters to pass (optional filters)
How much data to return at once (chunk size)

BIP runs the report's SQL, renders the output, and returns it as Base64-encoded data inside the SOAP response.
This is the same mechanism that Oracle Integration Cloud (OIC) uses under the hood when you configure a SOAP Adapter connection to BIP.

Find Your BIP Report Path
Before you can call a report, you need its catalog path. Here's how to find it:
Option A — From the BIP Catalog UI:

Log into Oracle Fusion → navigate to Tools → Reports and Analytics
Find your report → right-click → Properties
The path shown is your reportAbsolutePath

Find Your Report Parameter Names
If your report has parameters, you need the exact parameter names as defined in BIP.

In BIP → open your report → click Edit
Go to the Data Model (left panel) → click Parameters
The Name column shows the identifiers to use in the SOAP call

Reading the Response
After sending the request, Postman shows the raw SOAP response. It looks like this:
xml<soap:Envelope ...>
  <soap:Body>
    <ns0:runReportResponse ...>
      <ns0:runReportReturn>
        <ns0:reportBytes>
          77u/PD94bWwgdmVyc2lvbj0iMS4wIiBlbmNvZGluZz0iVVRGLTgiP...
        </ns0:reportBytes>
        <ns0:reportContentType>text/xml</ns0:reportContentType>
        <ns0:reportFileID/>
        <ns0:totalNumberOfPages>0</ns0:totalNumberOfPages>
      </ns0:runReportReturn>
    </ns0:runReportResponse>
  </soap:Body>
</soap:Envelope>
The long string inside <ns0:reportBytes> is your report data — Base64 encoded.

Decoding the Response
Quick test in Postman:

Copy the reportBytes value
Go to base64decode.org and paste it
You will see the raw XML data rows from your report

How the SOAP Structure Works
Every BIP SOAP call follows this structure — nothing changes except what is inside <pub:reportRequest>:

<soapenv:Envelope>                   ← Required wrapper — never changes
  <soapenv:Header/>                  ← Empty header — required but always empty
  <soapenv:Body>                     ← Body container
    <pub:runReport>                  ← The operation name — always "runReport"
      <pub:reportRequest>
        <pub:reportAbsolutePath>     ← ✏️ YOUR REPORT PATH
        <pub:sizeOfDataChunkDownload>← -1 for full response
        <pub:parameterNameValues>    ← ✏️ YOUR PARAMETERS
      </pub:reportRequest>
    </pub:runReport>
  </soapenv:Body>
</soapenv:Envelope>


What I Learned

The BIP SOAP endpoint is universal — the same URL and SOAP structure works for every report in the catalog. Only the path and parameters change, which makes this a reusable template across all integrations
Parameter names are case-sensitive and must exactly match what is defined in the BIP Data Model — a common source of hard-to-debug errors
The sizeOfDataChunkDownload = -1 setting is fine for development but for production reports with thousands of rows you should use chunked pagination to avoid timeout and memory issues
reportBytes is always Base64 regardless of report output type — BIP encodes the entire output (XML, CSV, PDF) the same way
Testing BIP reports in Postman before building the OIC flow saves significant time — you can verify the report path, confirm parameter names, and inspect the decoded XML structure before writing a single line of mapping logic
